!! Introduction

A parser recovers rather than throws. Meeting source it cannot fully make sense of, it renders what it can and records a diagnostic saying what it did, so a tiddler degrades on a gradient instead of collapsing, and the author hears about it.

The contract belongs to the parse result rather than to the wikitext parser, so any parser may populate it.

!! The diagnostic

A parse result carries a `diagnostics` array. Each entry holds:

|!Field |!Meaning |
|`from` |the character offset where the fault starts |
|`to` |the character offset where it ends |
|`severity` |`error`, `warning`, `info` or `hint`, worst first |
|`source` |what produced the diagnostic, by default the content type |
|`code` |a machine readable identifier, such as `unterminated-bold` |
|`message` |a sentence for the author |

`$tw.utils.makeParseDiagnostic(diagnostic,options)` normalises an entry and clamps its range to the source. Pass `{source, sourceLength}` as the options.

The [[parse-diagnostics Operator]] reads the array through the parse cache, and grades a tiddler by the worst severity it carries.

!! Recovering inside a rule

A wikitext rule that recovers silently reports itself by calling `this.parser.addDiagnostic(...)`, and leaves a node marked `isRecovered` carrying the exact source it stands for. A consumer therefore finds the damage in the tree as well as in the diagnostics, and the marked text always reconstructs the source it replaced.

!! Recovering a whole block

A block rule that cannot parse its block at all throws `$tw.utils.RecoverableParseError(diagnostic,tree)`. The parser records the diagnostic, resynchronises to the next blank line, and carries on with the rest of the tiddler. Any other error still propagates, so a genuine bug in a rule stays loud.

!! Writing a parser of your own

A parser for a new content type joins the contract by setting `diagnostics` on itself. It costs nothing else: the filter operator, the severity grading and the tree marking all follow.

```
function MyParser(type,text,options) {
	this.tree = [/* ... */];
	this.source = text;
	this.diagnostics = [];
	// on meeting something the grammar cannot read
	this.diagnostics.push($tw.utils.makeParseDiagnostic({
		from: start,
		to: end,
		severity: "warning",
		code: "my-grammar-fault",
		message: "The grammar could not read this construct"
	},{source: type, sourceLength: text.length}));
}
```
